Feature Engineering Art using R

Dataset Overview

Data

Data

Description

  • PassengerId -> type should be integers
  • Survived -> Survived or Not
  • Pclass -> Class of Travel
  • Name -> Name of Passenger
  • Sex -> Gender
  • Age -> Age of Passengers
  • SibSp -> Number of Sibling/Spouse aboard
  • Parch -> Number of Parent/Child aboard
  • Ticket
  • Fare
  • Cabin
  • Embarked -> The port in which a passenger has embarked.
    • C - Cherbourg,
    • S - Southampton,
    • Q - Queenstown

Feature 1

What’s in a name?

What titles we have?
train$Title <- gsub('(.*, )|(\\..*)', '', train$Name)

# Show title counts by sex
#ggplotly(
  ggplot(train, aes(x = Title, fill = Sex)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge")

#)
Group Categories
# Titles with very low cell counts to be combined to "rare" level
train <- group_category(data = train, feature = "Title", threshold = 0.03, update = TRUE)

# Show title counts by sex

  ggplot(train, aes(x = Title, fill = Sex)) +

Feature 2

Do families sink or swim together?

Family Size
train$Surname <- map_chr(train$Name, function(x) strsplit(x, split = '[,.]')[[1]][1])

# Create a family size variable including the passenger themselves
train$Fsize <- train$SibSp + train$Parch + 1

# Create a family variable 
train$Family <- paste(train$Surname, train$Fsize, sep='_')

# Use ggplot2 to visualize the relationship between family size & survival
#ggplotly(
  ggplot(train, aes(x = Fsize, fill = Survived)) +
    geom_bar(stat='count', position='dodge') +
    scale_x_continuous(breaks=c(1:11)) +
    labs(x = 'Family Size')

#)
Family Size Groups
# Discretize family size
train <- train %>% 
  mutate(FsizeD = ifelse(Fsize == 1, "Singleton",
                         ifelse(Fsize < 5, "Small", "Large")))

# Show family size by survival using a mosaic plot
#ggplotly(
  ggplot(train) + 
    geom_mosaic(aes(x = product(FsizeD, Survived),
                    fill = Survived)) +
    ylab("Family Size") +
    xlab("Survived") +
    theme(
        axis.text.x=element_blank(),
        axis.ticks.x=element_blank())

  #)
How it is related to the response variable?
corrplot::corrplot(cor2(train[, c(2, 17)]))

Feature 3

Cabin

# This variable appears to have a lot of missing values
train$Cabin[1:28]
 [1] NA            "C85"         NA            "C123"        NA           
 [6] NA            "E46"         NA            NA            NA           
[11] "G6"          "C103"        NA            NA            NA           
[16] NA            NA            NA            NA            NA           
[21] NA            "D56"         NA            "A6"          NA           
[26] NA            NA            "C23 C25 C27"
# The first character is the deck. For example:
strsplit(train$Cabin[2], NULL)[[1]]
[1] "C" "8" "5"
# Create a Deck variable. Get passenger deck A - F:
train$Deck<-factor(sapply(train$Cabin, function(x) strsplit(x, NULL)[[1]][1]))
ggplot(train, aes(x = Deck, fill = Survived)) +
  geom_bar(position = "dodge")

corrplot::corrplot(cor2(train[, c(2, 18)]))
